 ('CLOSTRIDIUM PERFRINGENS','<001>CLOSTRIDIUM PERFRINGENS<002>This is another infection characterized by nausea, stomach pain, cramps and diarrhea. The bacteria are hard to destroy because cooking does not always kill them.<003>FOOD-BORNE DISEASES<004><005>BACTERIAL DISEASES; BOTULISM; SALMONELLA; STAPHYLOCOCCUS FOOD POISONING; ESCHERICHIA COLI; STREPTOCOCCAL INFECTION<006><007><008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>https://www.jcfswinnipeg.org/Uploads/PDF/Chefs-Terminology.pdf (accessed date: 10-27-17)','2017-10-27 15:36:57','2017-10-27 15:36:57','abram','abram',116,NULL),
 ('SALMONELLA','<001>SALMONELLA<002>The food infection caused by salmonella bacteria exhibits symptoms that are similar to those of staph poisoning, though the disease may last longer. Most poultry carry these bacteria.<003>FOOD-BORNE DISEASES<004><005>BACTERIAL DISEASES; BOTULISM; CLOSTRIDIUM PERFRINGENS; STAPHYLOCOCCUS FOOD POISONING; ESCHERICHIA COLI; STREPTOCOCCAL INFECTION<006><007><008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>https://www.jcfswinnipeg.org/Uploads/PDF/Chefs-Terminology.pdf (accessed date: 10-27-17)','2017-10-27 15:38:05','2017-10-27 15:38:35','abram','abram',117,NULL),
 ('STAPHYLOCOCCUS FOOD POISONING','<001>STAPHYLOCOCCUS FOOD POISONING<002>Caused by toxins produced in foods by the bacterium Staphylococcus aureus. Staph is the most common food poisoning, characterized by vomiting, stomach cramps, diarrhea and prostration.<003>FOOD-BORNE DISEASES<004><005>BACTERIAL DISEASES; BOTULISM; CLOSTRIDIUM PERFRINGENS; ESCHERICHIA COLI; SALMONELLA; STREPTOCOCCAL INFECTION<006><007>Staph<008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>https://www.jcfswinnipeg.org/Uploads/PDF/Chefs-Terminology.pdf (accessed date: 10-27-17)','2017-10-27 15:40:05','2017-10-27 15:52:45','abram','abram',118,NULL);
INSERT INTO `pantasdb`.`thesaurus` (`title`,`maintext`,`date_entered`,`date_updated`,`entered_by`,`updated_by`,`id`,`image_location`) VALUES 
 ('ESCHERICHIA COLI','<001>ESCHERICHIA COLI<002>This bacterium causes severe illness, either as intoxication or an infection. Severe abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea and other symptoms result from E.coli intoxication. As an infection, E.coli causes intestinal inflammation and bloody diarrhea.<003>FOOD-BORNE DISEASES<004><005>BACTERIAL DISEASES; BOTULISM; CLOSTRIDIUM PERFRINGENS; SALMONELLA; STAPHYLOCOCCUS FOOD POISONING; STREPTOCOCCAL INFECTION<006><007>E.Coli<008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>https://www.jcfswinnipeg.org/Uploads/PDF/Chefs-Terminology.pdf (accessed date: 10-27-17)','2017-10-27 15:44:29','2017-10-27 15:44:29','abram','abram',119,NULL),
 ('STREPTOCOCCAL INFECTION','<001>STREPTOCOCCAL INFECTION<002>The symptoms of this disease are fever and sore throat.<003>FOOD-BORNE DISEASES<004><005>BACTERIAL DISEASES; BOTULISM; CLOSTRIDIUM PERFRINGENS; ESCHERICHIA COLI; SALMONELLA; STAPHYLOCOCCUS FOOD POISONING<006><007>Strep<008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>https://www.jcfswinnipeg.org/Uploads/PDF/Chefs-Terminology.pdf (accessed date: 10-27-17)','2017-10-27 15:46:05','2017-11-08 12:53:18','abram','abram',120,NULL),
 ('INFECTIONS','<001>INFECTIONS<002>Caused by bacteria (or other organisms) that get into the intestinal system and attack the body.<003>BACTERIAL DISEASES<004><005>INTOXICATIONS<006><007><008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>https://www.jcfswinnipeg.org/Uploads/PDF/Chefs-Terminology.pdf (accessed date: 10-27-17)','2017-10-27 15:56:41','2017-10-27 15:56:41','abram','abram',121,NULL);
INSERT INTO `pantasdb`.`thesaurus` (`title`,`maintext`,`date_entered`,`date_updated`,`entered_by`,`updated_by`,`id`,`image_location`) VALUES 
 ('INTOXICATIONS','<001>INTOXICATIONS<002>Caused by poisons (toxins) that the bacteria produce while they are growing in the food. It is these poisons, not the bacteria themselves, which cause the diseases. In most cases of food-borne illness, symptoms resemble intestinal flu and may last a few hours or even several days. Symptoms can range from mild to serious and include abdominal cramps, nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, fever and dehydration.<003>BACTERIAL DISEASES<004><005>INFECTIONS<006><007><008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>https://www.jcfswinnipeg.org/Uploads/PDF/Chefs-Terminology.pdf (accessed date: 10-27-17)','2017-10-27 15:57:54','2017-10-27 15:57:54','abram','abram',122,NULL),
 ('A LA CARTE','<001>A LA CARTE<002>It  was originally a French term (carte) for a piece of paper or cardboard and later a bill of fare or menu.  Today the term means according to the menu and that which is written down as available on the menu.  Refers to meal in which the diner selects individual items, paying for each, rather than taking a complete meal at a fixed price.<003><004><005><006><007><008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>https://whatscookingamerica.net/Glossary/A.htm (accessed date: 11-7-2017)','2017-11-07 10:31:38','2017-12-04 10:14:13','abram','abram',123,'alacarte.jfif'),
 ('FLOUR','<001>FLOUR<002>Primary ingredient in baking.<003>WHEAT BREAD<004>BANANA FLOUR; BATTERS; DOUGH; RICE FLOUR; GRAIN; GRAHAM FLOUR<005>BAKING; BREAD<006>Breadstuffs; Wheat flour<007><008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>Baking Handbook: for quick bread, yeast bread, cookies, cakes, pies, and pastries. Pasig City: Philippines. Anvil. c2009','2017-11-07 10:43:50','2017-11-07 10:43:50','abram','abram',124,NULL);
