 ('ASUETE','<001>ASUETE<002>In the vernacular are dark red seeds used for natural food coloring of vegetables, meat, and fish recipes. These are tear-shaped seeds found in clusters inside one-inch diameter balls covered with curly fibers. It is bland, but Philippine cooking considers it a â€œspiceâ€ that often goes with other spices. Recipes are enhanced by coloring. Some food colorings are synthetic and may prove harmful to health, but not asuete seeds. Theyâ€™re natural. Modern Philippine red dishes are â€œspicedâ€ up with them.<003>SPICES<004><005>ANISE; BASIL; BAY LEAF; BURNET; CAPERS; CARAWAY; CAYENNE PEPPER; CHERVIL; CHIVES; CINNAMON; CORIADER; CLOVE; CURRY; DILL; GARLIC; GINGER; HORSERADISH; JUNIPER; MACE; MARJORAM; MINT; NUTMEG; ONION; OREGANO; PAPRIKA; PARSLEY; PEPPER; POPPY; ROSEMARY; SAFFRON; RED PEPPER CHILI <006><007>Annato<008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>https://aboutphilippines.ph/documents-etc/Filipino-Cuisine.pdf (accessed date: 11-20-2017).','2017-11-20 10:37:31','2017-11-20 14:28:27','abram','abram',277,NULL),
 ('SPICES','<001>SPICES<002>Aromatic substance obtained from skome part of plants such as roots, shoots, fruits, leaves and back.  They are sold to market as a whole like ground speces, whole or crushed herbs, seeds and blend of spices, herbs and seasonings.<003><004>ANISE; ASUETE; BASIL; BAY LEAF; BURNET; CAPERS; CARAWAY; CAYENNE PEPPER; CHERVIL; CHIVES; CINNAMON; CORIADER; CLOVE; CURRY; DILL; GARLIC; GINGER; HORSERADISH; JUNIPER; MACE; MARJORAM; MINT; NUTMEG; ONION; OREGANO; PAPRIKA; PARSLEY; PEPPER; POPPY; ROSEMARY; SAFFRON; RED PEPPER CHILI <005>HERBS<006><007><008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>Reyes, Dick. (2006).  Introduction to Culinary Operations.  Paranaque City: AR Skills Development and Mangement Services, 2006.','2017-11-20 11:25:52','2017-11-20 14:28:50','abram','abram',278,NULL);
