 ('COOKING (MEAT PRESERVATION)','<001>COOKING (MEAT PRESERVATION)<002>When cooked to a temperature of 85 degrees centigrate, all putrefying bacteria are destroyed within a few minutes (Reyes and Roldan, 2006).<003>MEAT PRESERVATION METHODS<004><005>CANNING; DRYING; FREEZING; SALTING; SMOKING<006><007><008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>Reyes, Dick. (2006).  Introduction to Culinary Operations.  Paranaque City: AR Skills Development and Mangement Services, 2006.','2017-11-28 10:23:45','2017-11-28 10:26:35','abram','abram',413,NULL),
 ('DRYING (MEAT PRESERVATION)','<001>DRYING (MEAT PRESERVATION)<002>Place the meat into a salt and spice marinade.  After several days, it has to be hung and dried in a butcher drying store (Reyes and Roldan, 2006).<003>MEAT PRESERVATION METHODS<004><005>CANNING; COOKING; FREEZING; SALTING; SMOKING<006><007><008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>Reyes, Dick. (2006).  Introduction to Culinary Operations.  Paranaque City: AR Skills Development and Mangement Services, 2006.','2017-11-28 10:29:07','2017-11-28 11:31:38','abram','abram',414,NULL),
 ('FREEZING','<001>FREEZING<002>With temperature of 18 degrees centigrate, the putrefying of bacteria will stop (Reyes and Roldan, 2006).<003>MEAT PRESERVATION METHODS<004><005>CANNING; COOKING; DRYING; SALTING; SMOKING<006><007><008>Culinary Arts<009><0010>Reyes, Dick. (2006).  Introduction to Culinary Operations.  Paranaque City: AR Skills Development and Mangement Services, 2006.','2017-11-28 10:31:08','2017-11-28 10:31:08','abram','abram',415,NULL);
