 ('TOURIST ATTRACTIONS','<001>TOURIST ATTRACTIONS<002>Include a wide range of resources, both natural and human-created, that draw people away from their home environments to undergo a wide range of potentially overlapping experiences, including pleasure and enjoyment, relaxation, edu-cation, cultural edification, religious obligation, spiritual inspiration, health and wellness, nature appreciation or the discovering of oneâ€™s roots (Gunn & Var, 2002; Leiper, 1990; Lew, 1987).<003>TOURISM SYSTEM<004>CULTURAL ATTRACTIONS; EPHEMERAL ATTRACTIONS; ICONIC ATTRACTIONS; NATURAL ATTRACTIONS<005><006><007><008>LTM<009><0010>Timothy, D. J. (2015). Tourism and Trails : Cultural, Ecological and Management Issues. Bristol, UK: Channel View Publications.','2017-11-28 14:28:28','2017-12-06 13:55:28','abram','abram',445,''),
 ('CULTURAL ATTRACTIONS','<001>CULTURAL ATTRACTIONS<002>Attractiond of cultural origin as a manifestation of that culture without the original intention of serving tourism. May be tangible (building, landscape, object) or intangible (dance, song, art style).<003>ATTRACTIONS<004>CHURCES; HISTORICAL SITES; LANDMARKS; LOCAL ARTS AND CRAFTS; LOCAL FOLK CORE; MUSIC AND DANCE; PARKS; ZOOS<005>BUILT ATTRACTIONS; NATURAL ATTRACTIONS<006><007><008>LTM<009><0010>Stange, Jennifer. Tourism Destination Management Achieving Sustainable and Competitive Results.  Washington, DC: US Agency for International Development.','2017-11-28 14:32:18','2018-01-08 16:38:45','abram','abram',446,''),
