 ('EVENT MANAGEMENT','<001>EVENT MANAGEMENT<002>It is the process by which an event is planned, prepared, and produced. As with any other form of management, it encompasses the assessment, definition, acquisition, allocation, direction, control, and analysis of time, finances, people, products, services, and other resources to achieve objectives. An event managerâ€™s job is to oversee and arrange every aspect of an event, including researching, planning, organizing, implementing, controlling, and evaluating an eventâ€™s design, activities, and production (Silvers, Accessed date: 2018).<003><004>BUSINESS EVENTS; CIVIC EVENTS; CONVENTION EVENTS; EXHIBITIONS; FEASTS AND FESTIVALS; FUNDRAISING EVENTS; LEISURE EVENTS; MARKETING EVENTS; SPORTS EVENTS<005><006><007><008>LTM<009><0010>Silvers, J. (2003, October 26).  EMBOK Project.  Retrieved February 8, 2018, from http://www.juliasilvers.com/embok.htm#The_Definition_of_Event_Management.','2018-02-08 11:36:46','2018-02-08 13:31:33','abram','abram',1379,''),
 ('CIVIC EVENTS','<001>CIVIC EVENTS<002>An event comprised of or created by or for political parties, communities, or municipal or national government entities, scheduled alone or in conjunction with other events (Silvers, 2003).<003>EVENT MANAGEMENT<004><005>BUSINESS EVENTS; CONVENTION EVENTS; EXHIBITIONS; FEASTS AND FESTIVALS; FUNDRAISING EVENTS; LEISURE EVENTS; MARKETING EVENTS; SPORTS EVENTS<006><007><008>LTM<009><0010>Silvers, J. (2003, October 26).  EMBOK Project.  Retrieved February 8, 2018, from http://www.juliasilvers.com/embok.htm#The_Event_Genre_of_Event_Management.','2018-02-08 13:37:24','2018-02-08 13:37:24','abram','abram',1380,'');
